{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518385"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:04:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:04:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12914"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12914"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.83,0.05,0.06,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5352"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57229"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5352"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12914"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42688"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10382"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16347"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17335"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17655"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57229"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being admitted to hospital for intravenous fluids due to severe gastroenteritis with vomiting and diarrhoea. He has a medical history of epilepsy, for which he takes sodium valproate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApproximately five minutes ago, the patient was witnessed to suddenly lose consciousness and fall to the ground. His lips were observed to turn blue, and there was excessive drooling. The eyes rolled up, and he bit his tongue. The episode was marked by the entire body stiffening, followed by jerking and rhythmic movements of both arms and legs. These movements are ongoing on your arrival.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the next most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous midazolam 0.1 mg/kg stat","Intravenous levetiracetam 40-60 mg/kg over 5 minutes","Intravenous sodium valproate (patient\u0027s usual dose) over 20 minutes","Intravenous phenytoin 20 mg/kg over 30 minutes","Intravenous magnesium sulfate"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is experiencing an ongoing generalised tonic-clonic seizure, which requires immediate intervention to prevent complications such as status epilepticus. The first-line treatment for an acute seizure in the emergency setting is a benzodiazepine, due to its rapid onset of action and effectiveness in terminating seizures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous midazolam\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. It acts quickly to stop the seizure activity and is preferred in the acute setting for its rapid onset and ease of administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous levetiracetam\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiepileptic drug that can be used for seizure control, but it is not the first-line treatment for an acute seizure. It is typically considered if benzodiazepines are ineffective or if the seizure persists.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous sodium valproate\u003C/strong\u003E is the patient\u0027s usual antiepileptic medication, but it is not used acutely to terminate seizures. It may be considered in the management of status epilepticus if initial treatments fail.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous phenytoin\u003C/strong\u003E is another antiepileptic drug that can be used in the management of seizures, particularly if benzodiazepines are ineffective. However, it is not the first-line treatment in this acute scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous magnesium sulfate\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for the management of generalised tonic-clonic seizures. It is primarily used in the treatment of eclampsia-related seizures in pregnant women.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intravenous benzodiazepines are the first-line treatment for ongoing seizures in the emergency setting.","Prompt administration of benzodiazepines can help terminate seizures and prevent progression to status epilepticus.","Other antiepileptic drugs are considered if benzodiazepines are ineffective or if the seizure persists."],"references":["Kodankandath TV, Theodore D, Samanta D. Generalized Tonic-Clonic Seizure. [Updated 2023 Jul 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554496/#","Kienitz R, Kay L, Beuchat I, Gelhard S, von Brauchitsch S, Mann C, Lucaciu A, Sch\u00e4fer JH, Siebenbrodt K, Z\u00f6llner JP, Schubert-Bast S, Rosenow F, Strzelczyk A, Willems LM. Benzodiazepines in the Management of Seizures and Status Epilepticus: A Review of Routes of Delivery, Pharmacokinetics, Efficacy, and Tolerability. CNS Drugs. 2022 Sep;36(9):951-975. doi: 10.1007/s40263-022-00940-2. Epub 2022 Aug 16. PMID: 35971024; PMCID: PMC9477921.","Emergency Care Institute. Agency for Clinical Innovation. Seizures. NSW Government. n.d. Available from: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/networks/eci/clinical/clinical-tools/neurology/seizures","Queensland Ambulance Service. Clinical Practice Guidelines: Neurological/Seizures. Queensland Government. 2020. Available from: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/networks/eci/clinical/clinical-tools/neurology/seizures"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42688"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12914"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42688"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T17:46:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-30T08:27:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5352"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57229"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1106"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Seizure","synonyms":["Uncontrollable shaking","Seizures"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-07-23T10:18:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T20:10:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"contributions","id":"9806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/contributions/9806"},"attributes":{"finalizedAt":"2023-11-26T20:42:13+10:30","userDetails":{"name":"Hamza Ansari","title":"","isExpert":false,"position":"","training":"Student","credentials":"","institutionOther":"JNMC, Aligarh"}},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5352"}},"contributionTier":{"data":{"t